@deffn Function %string-compare @var{str1} @var{beg1} @var{past1} @var{str2} @var{beg2} @var{past2} @var{proc<} @var{proc=} @var{proc>}
@deffnx Function %string-compare-ci @var{str1} @var{beg1} @var{past1} @var{str2} @var{beg2} @var{past2} @var{proc<} @var{proc=} @var{proc>}
@deffnx Macro string-compare @var{S1} @var{S2} @var{proc<} @var{proc=} @var{proc>}
@deffnx Marco string-compare-ci @var{S1} @var{S2} @var{proc<} @var{proc=} @var{proc>}
Determine the @dfn{mismatch index} between the two substrings: the
largest index @math{i} such that for every @math{0 <= j < i},
@math{str1[j] = str2[j]}; that is, @math{i} is the first position that
does not match.

The mismatch index is always an index into @var{str1}; in the case of
equal strings, it is always @var{past1}; the functions observe the
protocol in this redundant case for uniformity.

The characters at the mismatch index are compared using @func{char<=?}
or @func{char-ci<=?}.  @var{proc<}, @var{proc=}, or @var{proc>} are
applied to the mismatch index, depending upon whether the substring of
@var{str1} is less than, equal to, or greater than the substring of
@var{str2}.  The result of the application is returned.

If we just want to have the mismatch index: We can use @func{values} as
value for @var{proc<}, @var{proc=} and @var{proc>}.  Another interesting
option is to use @code{(lambda (mismatch-index) #f)} or @code{(lambda
(mismatch-index) #t)}.

Examples:

@example
(string-compare "abcd" "abcd" values values values)
@result{} 5

(string-compare "abcd" "abcd12" values values values)
@result{} 5
@end example
