@defun vector-map* @var{proc} @var{vec0} @var{vec} ...
Construct a new vector of the shortest size of the vector arguments;
this is an extension of the @func{vector-map} function.  Each element at
index @var{i} of the new vector is mapped from the old vectors by:

@example
(@var{proc} @var{i}
  (vector-ref @var{vec0} @var{i})
  (vector-ref @var{vec} @var{i})
  )
@end example

The dynamic order of application of @var{proc} is unspecified.

@example
(vector-map (lambda (i x) (* x x))
              (vector-unfold (lambda (i x)
                               (values x (+ x 1)))

@result{} #(1 4 9 16)

(vector-map (lambda (i x y) (* x y))
              (vector-unfold (lambda (i x)
                               (values x (+ x 1)))
                             5 1)
              (vector-unfold (lambda (i x)
                               (values x (- x 1)))
                             5 5))
@result{} #(5 8 9 8 5)

(let ((count 0))
  (vector-map (lambda (ignored-index ignored-elt)
                (set! count (+ count 1))
                count)
              '#(a b)))
@result{} #(1 2) OR #(2 1)

(vector-map (lambda (i elt)
              (+ i elt))
            '#(1 2 3 4))
@result{} #(1 3 5 7)
@end example
@end defun

