@subsection Data types and conventions


A @dfn{range} is a pair representing a half--open interval of items.
The car of the pair if the included left--limit, called @var{start}; the
cdr is the excluded right--limit, called @var{past}.  Empty ranges
(pairs with equal values) are @strong{not} valid.

A @dfn{domain} is a sorted list of ranges.  Empty domains are empty
lists.  Ranges in a domain do not overlap and are not contiguous.  A
domain has the following format:

@example
((start1 . past1) (start2 . past2) (start3 . past3) ...)
@end example

@noindent
with the constraints:

@example
start1 < past1 < start2 < past2 < start3 < past3 < ...
@end example

The range and domain functions accept the following arguments:

@table @var
@item obj
Any object.

@item range
A valid range according to @func{%range?}.

@item domain
A valid domain according to @func{%domain?}.

@item start
The included left--limit of a range.

@item past
The excluded right--limit of a range.

@item item?
A unary predicate returning @true{} if the argument is a valid item.

@item item=?
An n--ary predicate returning @true{} if the all the arguments are
equal.  @func{char=?} is an example of such a function.

@item item<?
An n--ary predicate returning @true{} if the all the arguments, in the
given order, are in strict increasing order.  @func{char<?} is an
example of such a function.

@item item<=?
An n--ary predicate returning @true{} if the all the arguments, in the
given order, are in non--strict increasing order.  @func{char<=?} is an
example of such a function.

@item item-?
A binary function returning the number of items between the first
argument (included) and the second argument (excluded).  The arithmetic
@func{-} applied to integers is an example of such a function; for
characters we can use:

@example
(lambda (past start)
  (- (char->integer past)
     (char->integer start)))
@end example

@item item-copy
A unary function returning a copy of an item.  For ranges holding atomic
values (like characters or integers) it is fine to use @code{(lambda (x)
x)}.

@item item-next
A unary function returning the next value with respect to the argument.
For integers it can be @code{(lambda (x) (+ 1 x))}; for characters it
can be:

@example
(lambda (ch) (integer->char (+ 1 (char->integer ch))))
@end example


@item lower-bound
@itemx upper-bound
Values representing the included lower bound and the excluded upper
bounds for the items in ranges and domains.

The lower bound is used as first argument to the @var{item=?},
@var{item<?} and @var{item<=?} predicates.  The upper bound is used as
last argument to the @var{item=?}, @var{item<?} and @var{item<=?}
predicates.
@end table

